<body>

<header>
    <h1>Cloud Computing Reference Architecture</h1>
    <div class="tagline">Structured View of NIST Cloud Architecture</div>
</header>

<div class="container">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Introduction</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-intro.png" alt="Reference Architecture Overview">
        <p class="desc">
            Cloud Computing Reference Architecture is a tool used to describe, discuss, and develop system-specific
            cloud architectures using a common conceptual framework.
        </p>
        <p class="desc">
            The NIST Cloud Computing Reference Architecture provides a **vendor-neutral**, **high-level conceptual
            model** that helps in understanding cloud roles, activities, functions, and relationships.
        </p>
        <div class="exam">
            ðŸ“˜ Exam Line: NIST Cloud Reference Architecture is a vendor-neutral conceptual framework.
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD CONSUMER -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Consumer</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-consumer.png" alt="Cloud Consumer">
        <p class="desc">
            A cloud consumer can be an individual, organization, or user group that consumes cloud services.
            Consumers use cloud services to meet business or personal requirements without managing underlying
            infrastructure.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD PROVIDER -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Provider</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-provider.png" alt="Cloud Provider">
        <p class="desc">
            A cloud provider is responsible for delivering cloud services over the internet. This includes
            service deployment, orchestration, cloud service management, and ensuring security and privacy.
        </p>

        <h3>Service Deployment Models</h3>
        <img src="placeholder-deployment.png" alt="Deployment Models">
        <ul>
            <li>Public Cloud</li>
            <li>Private Cloud</li>
            <li>Hybrid Cloud</li>
            <li>Community Cloud</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>Service Orchestration</h3>
        <img src="placeholder-orchestration.png" alt="Service Orchestration">
        <p class="desc">
            Cloud providers use cloud operating systems such as OpenStack or CloudStack to orchestrate services.
            These platforms are built on:
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Virtualization:</b> Hypervisors enable IaaS service delivery</li>
            <li><b>Multitenancy:</b> Multiple customers share the same physical resources securely</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD SERVICE MANAGEMENT -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Service Management</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-management.png" alt="Cloud Management Interfaces">
        <p class="desc">
            Cloud providers offer multiple interfaces to provision and manage cloud resources.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li>Web Portal (GUI)</li>
            <li>Cloud Shell</li>
            <li>Cloud SDK</li>
            <li>Cloud CLI</li>
        </ul>

        <div class="tip">
            <b>Practical Insight:</b> Cloud adoption involves provisioning, access control, integration,
            monitoring, budgeting, and governance.
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- SECURITY & PRIVACY -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Security and Privacy</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-security.png" alt="Shared Responsibility Model">
        <p class="desc">
            Cloud security is governed by the Shared Responsibility Model, which clearly defines responsibilities
            between the provider and the consumer.
        </p>

        <h3>IaaS Responsibility</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Provider:</b> Hardware and hypervisor security</li>
            <li><b>Consumer:</b> Operating system security and patching</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>PaaS Responsibility</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Provider:</b> Infrastructure and OS security</li>
            <li><b>Consumer:</b> Application configuration and compliance</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>SaaS Responsibility</h3>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Provider:</b> End-to-end infrastructure security</li>
            <li><b>Consumer:</b> Configuration, customization, and data governance</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD BROKER -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Broker</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-broker.png" alt="Cloud Broker">
        <p class="desc">
            A cloud broker acts as an intermediary between cloud providers and consumers.
        </p>
        <ul>
            <li><b>Intermediation:</b> Adds value such as identity management or monitoring</li>
            <li><b>Aggregation:</b> Combines multiple services (e.g., SaaS platforms, cloud marketplaces)</li>
            <li><b>Arbitrage:</b> Dynamically selects best services from multiple providers</li>
        </ul>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD AUDITOR -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Auditor</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-auditor.png" alt="Cloud Auditor">
        <p class="desc">
            A cloud auditor provides independent assurance by evaluating security, privacy,
            performance, and compliance of cloud services.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CLOUD CARRIER -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Cloud Carrier</h2>
        <img src="placeholder-carrier.png" alt="Cloud Carrier">
        <p class="desc">
            A cloud carrier is responsible for providing connectivity and transport of cloud services.
            This includes network, telecom, and internet access infrastructure.
        </p>
    </section>

    <!-- SUMMARY -->
    <section class="section">
        <h2>Final Summary</h2>
        <p class="desc">
            The Cloud Computing Reference Architecture provides a structured and standardized way to
            understand cloud ecosystems. It clearly defines roles, responsibilities, and interactions,
            making it essential for cloud architects, administrators, and students.
        </p>
    </section>

</div>

